# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bulgarian-alphabet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/a-with-ring-above-cyrillic] A with ring above is used only in the alphabet of the Selkup language, where it represents the open-mid back rounded vowel /ɔ/ or the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The **Bulgarian Cyrillic alphabet** (Bulgarian: Българска кирилска азбука) is used to write the Bulgarian language.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The Cyrillic alphabet was originally developed in the First Bulgarian Empire during the 9th – 10th century AD at the Preslav Literary School.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The Cyrillic alphabet was used in the then much bigger territory of Bulgaria (including most of today's Serbia), North Macedonia, Kosovo, Albania, Northern Greece (Macedonia region), Romania and Moldova, officially from 893.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] It was also transferred from Bulgaria and adopted by the East Slavic languages in Kievan Rus' and evolved into the Belarusian, Russian and Ukrainian alphabets and the alphabets of many other Slavic (and later non-Slavic) languages.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Later, some Slavs modified it and added/excluded letters from it to better suit the needs of their own language varieties.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] In the 9th century, the Bulgarian Empire introduced the Glagolitic alphabet, devised by Saint Cyril and Saint Methodius.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The Glagolitic alphabet was gradually superseded in later centuries by the Cyrillic script, developed around the Preslav Literary School, Bulgaria at the end of the 9th century.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Yat was also known as "double e" (двойно е/е-двойно), and yus was also known as "big nasal sign" (голяма носовка), crossed yer (ъ кръстато), and "wide yer" (широко ъ).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Although Bulgarian uses the Cyrillic alphabet, some letter shapes in Bulgaria were made to look more 'Latin' in the 20th century (see the pictures on the right in the article), however they are rarely used today and most typefaces do not support them.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] With the accession of Bulgaria to the European Union on 1 January 2007, the Cyrillic script became the third official script of the European Union, following the Latin and Greek scripts.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The following table gives the letters of the Bulgarian alphabet, along with the IPA values for the sound of each letter.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The listed transliteration in the Official transliteration column (known as the Streamlined System) is official in Bulgaria and is listed in the Official orthographic dictionary (2012).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] For other transliteration standards see Romanization of Bulgarian.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The romanizations of these characters differ from the current version, ISO 9:1995, as it was never officially adopted as a Bulgarian standard.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Most letters in the Bulgarian alphabet stand for just one specific sound.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Five letters stand for sounds written in English with two or more letters.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] These letters are ч (ch), ш (sh), щ (sht), ю (yu), and я (ya).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Two additional sounds are written with two letters: these are дж (/dʒ/) and дз (/dz/).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The letter ь marks the softening (palatalization) of any consonant (except ж, ч, and ш) before the letter о, while ю and я after consonants mark the palatalization of the preceding consonant in addition to representing the vowels /u/ and /a/.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The names of most letters are simple representations of their phonetic values, with consonants being followed by /ɤ/ – thus the alphabet goes: /a/ – /bɤ/ – /vɤ/, etc.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] However, the name of the letter Й is "i-kratko" (*short i*), the name of Ъ is "er-golyam" (*large yer*), and the name of Ь is "er-malak" (*small yer*).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The grave accent is used to distinguish the pronoun ⟨ѝ⟩ 'her' from the conjunction ⟨и⟩ 'and'. Ѝ is not considered a separate letter but rather a special form of И.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Bulgarian is usually described as having a phonemic orthography, meaning that words are spelt the way they are pronounced with the exception of allophones (i.e. phones in complementary distribition).
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Since the time of Bulgaria's liberation in the late 19th century, the Bulgarian language has taken on a large number of words from Western European languages.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] In the years since the end of communism and the rise of technology, the tendency for borrowing has shifted mainly to English, where much computer-related terminology has entered and been inflected accordingly – again, in a wholly phonetic way.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The computer-related neologisms are often used interchangeably with traditional Bulgarian words, e.g.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] 'download' and 'upload' can be simply свалям and качвам (*svalyam* and *kachvam* – 'to bring down' and 'to put up').
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The insertion of English words directly into a Cyrillic Bulgarian sentence, while frowned upon, has been increasingly used in the media.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Brand names are also often not transcribed: WikiLeaks, YouTube, Skype – as opposed to Уикиликс, Ю-Тюб, Скайп.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] However, this is not always the case, as in the headline "Фейсбук vs. Гугъл" (official transliteration: *Feysbuk vs.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Note the inconsistency here – despite the insistence on Cyrillic, the "vs." has been retained in Roman script.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] The 2012 *Official Orthographic Dictionary of the Bulgarian Language* by the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences permits widely known proper names to remain in their original alphabet.
[src:bulgarian-alphabet/bulgarian-alphabet] Example sentences are given, all containing names of American IT companies: Yahoo, Microsoft, YouTube, PayPal, Facebook.
